Here's a simple HTML file that displays the current standard time and date on Mars. The code includes embedded CSS for styling and JavaScript for calculating and displaying the Martian time and date.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Mars Time and Date</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #282c34;
            color: white;
            text-align: center;
            padding: 50px;
        }
        h1 {
            font-size: 2.5em;
        }
        #mars-time {
            font-size: 2em;
            margin-top: 20px;
        }
        #mars-date {
            font-size: 1.5em;
            margin-top: 10px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Current Time and Date on Mars</h1>
    <div id="mars-date"></div>
    <div id="mars-time"></div>

    <script>
        function calculateMarsTime() {
            const earthDate = new Date();
            const marsSol = (earthDate.getTime() / 1000) / 88775.244; // Mars sol in seconds
            const marsDate = new Date(marsSol * 88775.244 * 1000); // Convert back to Earth time

            const marsDateString = marsDate.toUTCString().split(' ').slice(0, 4).join(' ');
            const marsTimeString = marsDate.toUTCString().split(' ')[4];

            document.getElementById('mars-date').innerText = `Date: ${marsDateString}`;
            document.getElementById('mars-time').innerText = `Time: ${marsTimeString}`;
        }

        setInterval(calculateMarsTime, 1000); // Update every second
        calculateMarsTime(); // Initial call
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
- The HTML structure includes a title and two divs to display the date and time on Mars.
- The CSS styles the page with a dark background and white text for better readability.
- The JavaScript function `calculateMarsTime` calculates the current time on Mars based on Earth time and updates the displayed date and time every second. The calculation uses the average length of a Martian sol (approximately 88775.244 seconds).
